soc.message

Class SOCGameTextMsg

  • java.lang.Object
    • soc.message.SOCMessage
      • soc.message.SOCMessageForGame
        • soc.message.SOCGameTextMsg
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable

    public class SOCGameTextMsg
extends SOCMessageForGame
    This message contains a text message for a SoC game. Seen by server or by human players on-screen, occasionally parsed by robots if they're expecting a debug message.

    Text announcements from the server are instead sent as SOCGameServerText to client versions 2.0.00 and newer. See that class javadoc for what game information is sent as text and what's sent as other message types.

    Text messages from clients in chat channels (not in games) use SOCChannelTextMsg instead.

    Author:
    Robert S Thomas
    See Also:
    Serialized Form

    • Field Detail

      • SERVERNAME

        public static final java.lang.String SERVERNAME
        "Server", the reserved nickname used when sending game text messages from the server itself, not chat messages from players.

        This is used only for pre-2.0.00 clients, because starting with that version, the server's announcement texts are sent as SOCGameServerText instead.

        Moved here in v2.0.00; previously declared in SOCServer and a string literal at clients.

        Since:
        2.0.00
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • SERVER_FOR_CHAT

        public static final java.lang.String SERVER_FOR_CHAT
        Reserved nickname ":" for server messages which should appear in the chat area. Can be used with any client version.

        When this "nickname" is used, the message text should end with " ::" because the original client would begin the text line with ":: " from nickname + ": ".

        Also used in SOCChannelTextMsg.

        Since:
        2.0.00
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • VERSION_FOR_DICE_RESULT_INSTEAD

        public static final int VERSION_FOR_DICE_RESULT_INSTEAD
        Version number (2000) where the server no longer sends dice roll results as a game text message.

        Clients older than v2.0.00 expect the server to announce dice roll results via text messages such as "j rolled a 2 and a 2." The client would then replace that on-screen with "Rolled a 4." to reduce visual clutter.

        Starting with v2.0.00, the client prints roll results from the SOCDiceResult message instead. So, the server doesn't send the roll result game text message to v2.0.00 or newer clients.

        Since:
        2.0.00
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • SOCGameTextMsg

        public SOCGameTextMsg(java.lang.String gameName,
                      java.lang.String nn,
                      java.lang.String tm)
        Create a GameTextMsg message.
        Parameters:
        gameName - name of game
        nn - nickname of sender, when message sent from server; announcements from the server (not from a player) use SERVERNAME or SERVER_FOR_CHAT. Server has always ignored this field from client, can send "-" but not blank.
        tm - message text, which may contain SOCMessage.sep2 but not SOCMessage.sep. For expected format when nn is SERVER_FOR_CHAT, see that constant's javadoc.

    • Method Detail

      • getNickname

        public java.lang.String getNickname()
        When sent from server, get the player's nickname for a chat message, or the server for game announcement text. In v2.0.00 and newer, can also be ":" (SERVER_FOR_CHAT) for server messages which should appear in the chat area (recent-chat recap, etc).

        When from client, server has always ignored this field; can send "-" but not blank.

        Returns:
        the player's nickname, or SERVERNAME, or SERVER_FOR_CHAT (":") for server messages which should appear in the chat area (recap, etc)

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Description copied from class: SOCMessage
        Simple human-readable delimited representation, used for debug purposes: SOCPutPiece:game=test5|playerNumber=3|pieceType=0|coord=40a
        Could also be used by a SOCServer.recordGameEvent(String, SOCMessage) implementation.

        Within this representation, message parameters should be in same order used by SOCMessage.toCmd() and parseDataStr(..). Should be parseable by SOCMessage.parseMsgStr(String) which calls SOCMessage.stripAttribNames(String), which your class can override if needed.

        Overrides:
        toString in class SOCMessageForGame
        Returns:
        a human readable form of the message
        See Also:
        SOCMessage.toCmd()
